13 Existing law provides that, with certain exceptions, the seizure and disposition
14 of an animal which an officer discovers is being treated cruelly does not apply to
15 any animal which is located on land being employed for an agricultural use. (NRS
16 574.055) Section 3 removes this exception.
17 Existing law provides that a person who engages in certain acts of torture or
18 cruelty to animals is guilty of a misdemeanor for a first offense, except if the
19 person: (1) willfully and maliciously engages in such an act, the person is guilty of
20 a category D felony; or (2) commits the act to threaten, intimidate or terrorize
21 another person, the person is guilty of a category C felony. (NRS 574.100) Section
22 4 of this bill provides instead that a willful and malicious violation where the act
23 causes the death of the animal and committing the act to threaten, intimidate or
24 terrorize another person are both a category B felony, punishable by imprisonment
25 in the state prison for a minimum term of 1 year and a maximum term of 6 years.
26 Existing law prohibits the owner, possessor or person in charge or custody of a
27 maimed, diseased, disabled or infirm animal from abandoning the animal, leaving
28 the animal to die in certain public places or allowing the animal to lie in certain
29 public places for more than 3 hours after the person receives notice that the animal
30 is left disabled. A violation of this prohibition is a misdemeanor. (NRS 574.110)
31 Existing law also prohibits a person from abandoning an animal in any other
32 circumstance, with certain exceptions for feral cats. A violation of this prohibition
33 is a misdemeanor that is subject to certain enhanced penalties under certain
34 circumstances. (NRS 574.100) Section 4 prohibits the abandonment of an animal in
35 all circumstances, with certain exceptions for feral cats. Section 15.5 of this bill
36 repeals the existing law relating to the abandonment of a maimed, diseased,
37 disabled or infirm animal. As a result of this change, the abandonment of an animal,
38 regardless of the health of the animal, is subject to the same penalties and penalty
39 enhancements.
40 Existing law provides that a person who engages in certain acts of torture of or
41 cruelty to a police animal is guilty of: (1) a category D felony if the police animal is
42 not totally disabled or killed; and (2) a category C felony if the police animal is
43 totally disabled or killed. (NRS 574.105) Section 5 of this bill increases these
44 penalties to a category B felony if the police animal is totally disabled or killed,
45 punishable by imprisonment in the state prison for a minimum term of not less than
46 1 year and a maximum term of not more than 6 years.
47 Existing law sets forth the applicability of certain provisions relating to cruelty
48 to animals. (NRS 574.200) Section 6 of this bill provides that these provisions do
49 not prohibit providing humane relief to an animal to prevent the further suffering of
50 the animal when the animal is gravely injured.
51 Existing law requires that if a person is lawfully arrested for certain crimes
52 against animals and an animal owned or possessed by the person is impounded by
53 the county, city or other local government in connection with the arrest, the person
54 must be notified of his or her right to request a hearing within 5 days. If the person
55 does not request a hearing, or if the owner of the animal has not been identified
56 within 5 days after the arrest, the county, city or other local government which
57 impounded the animal is required to transfer ownership of the animal to an animal
58 rescue organization, animal shelter or another person who is able to provide
59 adequate care and shelter to the animal. (NRS 574.055, 574.203) Sections 3 and 7
60 of this bill require the owner to be notified of his or her right to request a hearing
61 within 7 calendar days after receiving the notice. Sections 3 and 7 also provide
62 that, if the arrested and detained person does not request a hearing, or the owner of
63 the animal has not been identified within 7 calendar days after the arrest, the animal
64 is forfeited to the county, city or other local government which took possession of
65 the animal, who must then dispose of the animal as the county, city or other local
66 government sees fit.
