67 Existing law provides that the knowing, purposeful or reckless killing or
68 injuring of an animal may be an act that constitutes domestic violence. (NRS
69 33.018) Existing law authorizes a court, by a temporary order, to enjoin the adverse
70 party named in an application for an order for protection against domestic violence
71 from: (1) physically injuring, threatening to injure or taking possession of any
72 animal that is owned or kept by the applicant for the order or a minor child and any
73 animal that is owned or kept by the adverse party; and (2) physically injuring or
74 threatening to injure any animal that is owned or kept by the adverse party. Existing
75 law further authorizes the court, by extended order, to specify arrangements for the
76 possession and care of any animal owned or kept by the adverse party, applicant or
77 minor child. (NRS 33.030) Section 8 of this bill authorizes the court, by temporary
78 order, to enjoin the adverse party from taking possession of an animal that is owned
79 or kept by the adverse party.
80 Existing law requires, if a child is adjudicated delinquent for an unlawful act
81 that involves cruelty to or torture of an animal, the juvenile court to order the child
82 to participate in counseling or other psychological treatment. (NRS 62E.680)
83 Sections 1.9 and 9 of this bill require the juvenile court to order such a child to also
84 undergo a psychological evaluation.
85 Existing law provides that if a person is convicted for an unlawful act involving
86 animal cruelty, a court may order, as a condition of probation, the person to submit
87 to a psychiatric evaluation and participate in counseling or therapy. (NRS
88 176A.416) Sections 1.9 and 11 of this bill authorize a court to also order such a
89 person to participate in a rehabilitative or educational program.
90 Section 2 of this bill applies certain definitions in existing law relating to
91 animal cruelty to the provisions of section 1.9.
92 Existing law prohibits a person from leaving a pet in a motor vehicle under
93 certain circumstances. (NRS 202.487) Existing law authorizes a peace officer, an
94 animal control officer, certain governmental officers and certain other persons to
95 use any reasonable means necessary to protect a pet left unattended in a motor
96 vehicle and to remove the pet from the motor vehicle without incurring civil
97 liability, under certain circumstances. (NRS 202.487) Section 14 of this bill
98 provides that a person who is immune from civil liability for taking such actions is
99 also immune from criminal liability. Section 14 also authorizes any other person to
100 whom existing law does not grant immunity from civil liability to use any
101 reasonable means necessary to protect a pet left unattended and to remove the pet
102 from the motor vehicle without incurring civil or criminal liability if the person: (1)
103 determines that the motor vehicle is locked or there is no other reasonable way to
104 protect the pet or remove the pet from the vehicle; (2) reports the violation to a law
105 enforcement agency or certain other governmental entities; (3) remains with the pet
106 until informed that his or her presence is no longer needed by such law enforcement
107 agency or other governmental entity; and (4) cooperates with certain persons who
108 respond to a request for assistance.
